Beyonwiz remote control codes

Infra Red (IR) remote control codes for Beyonwiz series are sent using
the NEC protocol. This protocol uses 4 bytes of data. The first two bytes
form a 16-bit "vendor" code. The remaining two bytes are used to encode
an 8-bit "key" code by sending an 8-bit value for the key as the first
byte followed by an inverted bit pattern in the second byte.

The hardware and drivers decode the protocol and translate the raw IR
values into standard Linux input events. enigma2 uses keymap.xml to
convert the Linux events into enigma2 events.

The set of decoded IR codes is selected using /proc/stb/ir/rc/type
The accepted values are dependent on the hardware model:

_______________________
Beyonwiz T2 / T3 / T4
=======================
Value  Vendor code set
-----  ---------------
0      All supported*
3      HDx (0x0933)
5      Beyonwiz T3 (0xABCD)
6      Beyonwiz (0x02F2)
7      Beyonwiz (0x02F3)
8      Beyonwiz (0x02F4)
10     Beyonwiz U4 (0xAE97)

_______________________
Beyonwiz U4
=======================
Value  Vendor code set
-----  ---------------
506    Beyonwiz T3 (0xABCD)
507    Beyonwiz U4 (0xAE97)
508    Beyonwiz T2/T4 (0x02F2)
509    Beyonwiz U4/T4/T2 (0x02F3)
510    Beyonwiz T2/T4 (0x02F4)

The "All supported*" mode (/proc/stb/ir/rc/type value 0) is the default
on Beyonwiz T2/T3/T4 models. The driver will decode all the supported
vendor codes and as a result the device will respond to any of the
supported remote controls. Beyonwiz U4 does not support this mode.

The following tables show the IR code to Linux input event mapping for
various Beyonwiz remote controls. Please consult keymap.xml and source
code to learn how enigma2 handles these codes.

Notes:

Beyonwiz T3 production models shipped with a remote control that only
supports the 0xABCD vendor code. There was a limited number of T3 remotes
sent to some beta testers and these remotes have a small switch in the
battery compartment that can be used to switch the remote control vendor
code to 0xAE97

Beyonwiz T2 and T4 remotes support switching between 0x02F2, 0x02F3 and
0x02F4 vendor codes, with 0x02F2 being the default setting. The T2 and T4
remotes do not support the T3 vendor codes.

Beyonwiz U4 remote can be switched between 0xAE97 and 0x02F3, with 0xAE97
being the factory default. Even though both vendor codes for the U4 are
also used by T2, T3 and T4 remotes, the button sets are not identical.
The U4 remote lacks some buttons and adds new ones. The resulting scheme
allows both backwards and forwards compatibility, such that a remote from
any model Beyonwiz can be used together with any other model Beyonwiz.

